“However, we do not see a similar response from the United States,” he said.
“Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances there is no chance of us unilaterally disarming ourselves first.”
While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to an approach divided into stages for the nuclear power that would lead to North Korea being rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statement seemed significant, as it did not reject a unilateral nuclear solution as Pyongyang had done before.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim promised to work towards "decommissioning nuclear weapons on the Korean Peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first dismantle its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also declined negotiations to ease harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on “decommissioning first” and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its purpose through coercion and even object to “the declaration of ending the war,” Ri says.
“The notion that sanctions can get us on our knees is a dream come true for those people who lack knowledge about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions deepen our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that U.S. leaders highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korea’s leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the party to this issue of nuclear disarmament was South Korea and not the United States, the Korean Peninsula nuclear disarmament would not have come to such a deadlock.”
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different than last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s future ability to reach the U.S. mainland with rockets was inevitable after “Mr Evil President” Trump called Kim a “rocketman” on a suicide mission.
This year in the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take action on disarmament, but it said that much work still remains and that sanctions must remain until North Korea is disarmed.
