Harvard students take courses on getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has prompted all doctoral students to improve their sleep habits in an effort to combat the growing macho culture of studying through caffeine-filled “dykes.”
An academic study found that students at the world’s leading universities are often clueless when it comes to the very foundations of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he considers to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
“At the end of the day, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why can’t I know this until now, in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was organized for the first time this year, explains to students the importance of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improving their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course includes a range of interactive tasks.
In part of the course there is a picture of a student room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, coaches and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of good sleep habits.
In another part, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know it won’t change students’ behavior directly.
But we believe they have the right to know – just as one has the right to know about the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in the "dying" still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Ensuring that you have enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said – even to avoid weight gain because insomnia puts the brain in starvation mode and makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course and has read one of his courses last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course was an eye-opener and inspired him to campaign for a campus-wide course.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all doctoral students to complete a similar study program before they start their studies at the high-performing institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when to lie down and when to wake up and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can cause you to turn on the clock, leading to insomnia problems.
