The pillars of the province of Central Sulawesi's economy are fisheries and agriculture, particularly in the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also significant in the province, but it is mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have suffered from tsunamis several times in the last hundred years, according to Indonesia’s Disaster Management Authority.
In 1938, more than 200 people were killed by a tsunami that destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
Also in 1996, the western Donggala was hit by a tsunami that killed nine people.
Indonesia lies in the circumpacific seismic aging, which is often affected by earthquakes.
Here are some of the biggest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian Aceh province on northern Sumatra on 26 December triggered a tsunami that hit 14 countries. 226,000 people died along the Indian Ocean coasts. More than half of them were in Aceh.
2005: A series of severe earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: An earthquake with magnitude 6.8 on the Richter scale struck south of Java, Indonesia’s most populous island, triggering a tsunami that struck across the southern coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: An earthquake of magnitude 7.6 struck near the town of Padang, the capital of the province of Western Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: An earthquake of magnitude 7.5 struck one of the Mentawai Islands off Sumatra. A tsunami of up to ten meters was triggered. Dozens of villages were destroyed and around 300 people were killed.
2016: A ground earthquake struck the Pidie Jaya administrative area of Aceh, causing destruction and panic, as people were reminded of the devastation of the deadly earthquake and tsunami in 2004.
This time no tsunami was triggered, but more than 100 people were killed by buildings that collapsed.
2018: Major earthquakes hit the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok. More than 500 people died, most on the northern side of the island.
